Information retrieval is ubiquitous. As you are reading these lines, millions of data items are downloaded every minute from large distributed databases, residing "on the cloud". Numerous online services let users query public datasets for items such as map directions, stock quotes, and flight prices, to name a few. Unfortunately, such queries have the potential to reveal sensitive information about the users, thereby compromising their privacy. A great deal of research has been devoted to methods that guarantee the security and integrity of the data. Less work, however, has been devoted to protecting the privacy of the user. Efficient and reliable retrieval of information from distributed databases, with information-theoretic guarantees of user privacy, was the primary focus of this project.

The relevant area of research, known as private information retrieval (PIR), was established over 20 years ago. PIR has been traditionally studied in theoretical computer science and cryptography, with emphasis on the complexity of the communication between the user and the servers that store the database. While major breakthroughs have been achieved in this area over the years, the prevailing paradigm has always been that of replicating the database on several servers. Such replication leads to a significant storage overhead, which is undesirable. Moreover, motivated by advances in coding for distributed storage, it was recently recognized that if database replication is replaced by database coding, the full power of coding-theoretic methods can be brought to bear on the problem. The goal of this project was to follow-up on the database coding idea, and follow it through to its ultimate potential. In furtherance of this goal, we have specifically obtained the following results:

Construction and analysis of PIR schemes with low download and access complexity as well as reduced storage requirements;
Design of PIR array codes with optimal server rate, functional PIR codes, and batch codes for distributed storage;
Design and analysis of PIR codes featuring both locality and availability, constructed from subspaces;
Improved schemes for asymptotically optimal repair of regenerating codes for distributed storage, featuring a lower sub-packetization than existing constructions;
Constructions and bounds for functional PIR and batch codes, extending and generalizing our earlier results on k-server PIR codes;
Invention, design, and analysis of distributed private proximity retrieval schemes, along with constructions thereof from covering designs.


In addition, we have also investigated a variety of challenging and important problems in the related disciplines of coding theory, combinatorics, and discrete mathematics. Our results along these lines include: 

Proof of the existence of large sets of designs for most admissible parameters, using a new probabilistic method;
Enumeration of distinct binary k-decks, with applications to distributed retrieval of information stored in DNA;
Efficient low-power cooling codes for high-performance interconnects, controlling both peak temperature and average power consumption;
Explicit constructions of Baranyai partitions for quadruples, making it possible to generate any specific parallel class in linear time;
Coding schemes for racetrack memories, correcting over-shift and under-shifts errors and reconstructing data from multiple readout heads;
Constructions, properties, and enumeration of constrained de Bruijn sequences and codes, with applications to the racetrack readout channel.


On the education and professional development front, our investigation has provided a stimulating and innovative research environment for graduate students and postdoctoral researchers, encouraging team-work across university boundaries and collaboration across disciplines. One student graduated during the course of this project; she is now employed with the information technology industry in California. Our research has also actively engaged undergraduate students during summer visits to UC San Diego.

